post_text: Join us for a KCSD Virtual Art Show on Friday, May 1st starting at 6 PM to celebrate the artwork our students have created! Artwork of all types is welcome from ALL students (not just students in art classes!), whether it is new or something you have created during the school year. (KCSD staff are also welcome to send their artwork!) Please photo or scan 1-2 pieces of your artwork and email it - with the artists' name, grade, and school - to webmaster@kcsdschools.net by Thursday, April 30th. We will upload all the artwork into a folder that we will share online so that people can virtually "browse" through our students' creations to celebrate with them! (The artwork will remain online - we are just "launching" that evening.) #myKCSD #KCStrong

post_text: Food Site Update: On Monday, April 20th, the Camden High pick up location will reopen. We return to 4 pick up sites: Bethune Elementary, Blaney Elementary, Camden High and North Central Middle. Breakfast pick up is from 7-9 a.m. and lunch from 11 a.m.-1 p.m. At pick up sites, we will continue to collect the names of the parent and child receiving the meals, so you no longer have to have the child with you to receive food. (This only applies to pick up sites; there is no change for food delivered by our buses.) #myKCSD #KCSDStrong

post_text: Woolard Technology Center Principal Gordon Morris, his father Buster, administrator John Thompson and Superintendent Dr. Shane Robbins delivered 250 plants to KershawHealth as gifts for their employees. The plants were grown in WTC's greenhouse by Agriculture Science students earlier in the semester as part of their Future Farmers of America (FFA) Annual Plant Sale. We are glad to be able to turn our students' hard work into gifts for our health care workers! #myKCSD #KCStrong

If you haven‚Äôt completed it yet, paper questionnaires are in the mail headed your way. Households receiving the paper questionnaire can still respond online or by phone, or they can return it by mail in the enclosed envelope. post_text: KCSD salutes all of our community health care workers who are working so hard to care for our loved ones! This is a great reminder that our KCSD school nurses care deeply for the well-being of our students, and our health care workers are community helpers who are working hard to keep our community and themselves safe. post_text: Join KCSD in honoring our Military Children! April is designated as the Month of the Military Child, a time to honor the sacrifices made by military families worldwide with an emphasis on the experience of the dependent children of military members serving at home and overseas. The Theme for 2020 is Overcoming Challenges-Adapting. Visit our website at www.kcsdschools.net/military for an activity calendar to encourage families to celebrate their military children. You can share photos and posts with the hashtag #KCSDMilitary2020.

If you have any questions about the bus routes, please call or email your child‚Äôs school transportation office:

Camden Area Bus Office - 425-8943
Elgin Area Bus Office - 438-2135
Lugoff Area Bus Office - 438-8017
North Central Area Bus Office- 425-8976 OR 424-2849

Meal delivery & pick-up will resume on April 13. Also, we greatly appreciate the following businesses who donated bags for our families: Food Lion of Elgin, IGA of Elgin, Piggly Wiggly of Camden, and Sonic of Lugoff. #myKCSD #KCSDStrong #KCStrong

post_text:
The groundbreaking ceremony for the new Kershaw County School District elementary school in the North Central area was held on Monday, November 18 at noon. The $21 million school will be built on property adjacent to North Central Middle School.

This summer, the Kershaw County School Board voted to close Mt. Pisgah Elementary School, Baron DeKalb Elementary School and Bethune Elementary School and build a new elementary school that can serve up to 600 students. The new school will open in the 2021-22 school year.

The school will be built by Hood Construction. Architects for the project are Pike-McFarland-Hall Associates, Inc. & UWPD Architecture, Inc.
text:
The groundbreaking ceremony for the new Kershaw County School District elementary school in the North Central area was held on Monday, November 18 at noon. The $21 million school will be built on property adjacent to North Central Middle School.

This summer, the Kershaw County School Board voted to close Mt. Pisgah Elementary School, Baron DeKalb Elementary School and Bethune Elementary School and build a new elementary school that can serve up to 600 students. The new school will open in the 2021-22 school year.

The school will be built by Hood Construction. Architects for the project are Pike-McFarland-Hall Associates, Inc. & UWPD Architecture, Inc.
